00:01:22.320 --> 00:01:24.810
So let's start.

00:01:24.810 --> 00:01:26.110
&gt;&gt; J.D. Vance: Sure.

00:01:26.110 --> 00:01:28.000
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:Surely, when
you started to write this book,

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:31.270
in your wildest imagination you
could not have thought you were

00:01:31.270 --> 00:01:32.660
going to write a New
York Time's Best Seller

00:01:32.660 --> 00:01:34.130
on your first book, or did you?

00:01:34.130 --> 00:01:36.570
&gt;&gt; J.D. Vance: No, I certainly
didn't think that I would.

00:01:36.570 --> 00:01:37.870
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:So was it,

00:01:37.870 --> 00:01:40.060
where did the idea for
the book come from?

00:01:40.060 --> 00:01:43.130
&gt;&gt; J.D. Vance: Well, it
actually started in law school.

00:01:43.130 --> 00:01:46.040
And really, the genesis was that
I was very interested in some

00:01:46.040 --> 00:01:49.310
of the concepts and the ideas
that I wrote about in the book,

00:01:49.310 --> 00:01:50.610
and most specifically this question

00:01:50.610 --> 00:01:52.900
about vulnerability
in the United States.

00:01:52.900 --> 00:01:56.310
And at Yale, we had to write this,
basically this thesis by the end

00:01:56.310 --> 00:01:59.430
of our 3rd year in order to
graduate, and I really wanted

00:01:59.430 --> 00:02:02.430
to write it about, sort of, the
legal and policy implications

00:02:02.430 --> 00:02:06.110
of social mobility in the United
States, or the lack therefore.

00:02:06.110 --> 00:02:10.480
And the more that I started to talk
through the idea and the people

00:02:10.480 --> 00:02:15.630
that were advising me, the more,
and especially my primary adviser,

00:02:15.630 --> 00:02:17.260
a woman named Amy Chua,
who, herself,

00:02:17.260 --> 00:02:20.260
is a pretty successful
author, she continued.

00:02:20.260 --> 00:02:21.560
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:She's
the author of Tiger.

00:02:21.560 --> 00:02:23.950
&gt;&gt; J.D. Vance: She's the author of
Battle Hymn of the Tiger Mother.

00:02:23.950 --> 00:02:26.050
And she encouraged
me, more and more,

00:02:26.050 --> 00:02:30.180
to bring my personal experiences
to bear, because she thought

00:02:30.180 --> 00:02:33.120
that I could write something
that was both, hopefully,

00:02:33.120 --> 00:02:37.150 position:56%
intellectually interesting, but also
personally and emotionally powerful.

00:02:37.150 --> 00:02:39.980
And as I continued
to write the book,

00:02:39.980 --> 00:02:42.470
I was obviously a little
resistant to that at first,

00:02:42.470 --> 00:02:44.460
I didn't like the idea of
opening up my personal life

00:02:44.460 --> 00:02:46.430
and telling all these
personal stories.

00:02:46.430 --> 00:02:49.460
But the more that I wrote, the more
that I realized that to the degree

00:02:49.460 --> 00:02:51.000
that I had a unique contribution.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:53.340
It was that I understood
these things from the inside,

00:02:53.340 --> 00:02:55.340
as opposed to just as an academic.

00:02:55.340 --> 00:02:56.640
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:All right.

00:02:56.640 --> 00:02:58.500
So you had the idea
of writing a book.

00:02:58.500 --> 00:03:01.090
How long did it take
you to write the book?

00:03:01.090 --> 00:03:04.080
&gt;&gt; J.D. Vance: Well, I was
always working on it part time,

00:03:04.080 --> 00:03:06.350
so I always had another job
while I was writing the book.

00:03:06.350 --> 00:03:09.400
And I think that it probably
took me about 2 1/2 years.

00:03:09.400 --> 00:03:14.650
So I started writing it, yeah,
towards the middle of 2013,

00:03:14.650 --> 00:03:17.110
and I finished towards
the end of 2015.

00:03:17.110 --> 00:03:18.410
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:So
did you write in long hand,

00:03:18.410 --> 00:03:19.730
or did you do it on a computer?

00:03:19.730 --> 00:03:21.570
&gt;&gt; J.D. Vance: No, I
did it on my computer.

00:03:21.570 --> 00:03:23.280
My handwriting is absolutely
terrible.

00:03:23.280 --> 00:03:24.580
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:All right.

00:03:24.580 --> 00:03:28.140
And so, as you're writing it, did
you have any publisher lined up,

00:03:28.140 --> 00:03:30.770
or did you just say, I'll write
it and then I'll get a publisher?

00:03:30.770 --> 00:03:32.070
&gt;&gt; J.D. Vance: Yeah.

00:03:32.070 --> 00:03:33.370
So this is interesting.

00:03:33.370 --> 00:03:34.830
And, in some ways, it exemplifies
something that I really write

00:03:34.830 --> 00:03:36.720
about in the book, this
idea of social capital

00:03:36.720 --> 00:03:41.630
and how social connections can have
these really important benefits.

00:03:41.630 --> 00:03:45.600
So because of Amy, when I started
to really think about making this

00:03:45.600 --> 00:03:48.850
into a book project, you know, she
said, okay, let me introduce you

00:03:48.850 --> 00:03:50.720
to these people that I know
in the publishing world.

00:03:50.720 --> 00:03:54.430
And so, one of the people she
introduced me to is this woman,

00:03:54.430 --> 00:03:57.450
who eventually became my agent, and
really good friend, Tina Bennett,

00:03:57.450 --> 00:04:01.140
and as I quickly learned, when you
have an idea and you have somebody

00:04:01.140 --> 00:04:04.570
like Tina really advocating
for it, the publishing,

00:04:04.570 --> 00:04:08.220
finding a publisher
is, is relatively easy.

00:04:08.220 --> 00:04:11.140
And that's sort of what happened
with me, is that the hard part

00:04:11.140 --> 00:04:14.260
for me was getting into
the agent publishing world,

00:04:14.260 --> 00:04:16.860
and then once I was there it
wasn't so hard to find a publisher.

00:04:16.860 --> 00:04:18.160
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:Sometimes
first authors,

00:04:18.160 --> 00:04:20.380
first time authors say, you
know, this shouldn't be that hard

00:04:20.380 --> 00:04:23.100
to write a book, and then about
half way through, they say,

00:04:23.100 --> 00:04:24.730
how can I get out of this project?

00:04:24.730 --> 00:04:26.420
So were you in that category?

00:04:26.420 --> 00:04:28.340
Did you ever want to abandon it?

00:04:28.340 --> 00:04:30.170
&gt;&gt; J.D. Vance: Yeah, I
definitely did want to abandon it,

00:04:30.170 --> 00:04:31.470
and if my wife is here,

00:04:31.470 --> 00:04:34.910
she can probably tell you how
miserable I was about that 50% way

00:04:34.910 --> 00:04:36.970
through the writing process.

00:04:36.970 --> 00:04:40.650
Yeah, I mean, for me, what was
so tough is that once I got

00:04:40.650 --> 00:04:42.330
about half way through
the book, you know,

00:04:42.330 --> 00:04:44.540
obviously it was too
late to give up.

00:04:44.540 --> 00:04:46.410
I couldn't just stop writing it.

00:04:46.410 --> 00:04:48.560
But, you know, writing
an additional 40,

00:04:48.560 --> 00:04:51.700
50,000 words just seemed
so imposing.

00:04:51.700 --> 00:04:56.140
And I realized then what I didn't
realize going into the project is

00:04:56.140 --> 00:05:01.420
that I probably had about a 10 to
1 ratio of words typed to words

00:05:01.420 --> 00:05:03.220
that made it into the
final manuscript.

00:05:03.220 --> 00:05:07.620
And so I just didn't realize what
a long slog it would be until I was

00:05:07.620 --> 00:05:09.080
about halfway through it.

00:05:09.080 --> 00:05:11.290
And yeah, I definitely
thought to myself,

00:05:11.290 --> 00:05:13.820
would it be possible
to get out of this?

00:05:13.820 --> 00:05:16.540
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:So, your
publisher had some confidence.

00:05:16.540 --> 00:05:19.240
The initial print run was 10,000.

00:05:19.240 --> 00:05:20.540
&gt;&gt; J.D. Vance: Right.

00:05:20.540 --> 00:05:23.100
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:So
10,000 isn't 500,000,

00:05:23.100 --> 00:05:25.550
but 10,000 is good
for a first author.

00:05:25.550 --> 00:05:29.000
At what point, when the book
came out, did people say, hey,

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:30.520
there aren't enough
copies out anymore,

00:05:30.520 --> 00:05:32.280
and we have to go print more?

00:05:32.280 --> 00:05:33.580
&gt;&gt; J.D. Vance: Yeah.

00:05:33.580 --> 00:05:37.400
So this happened relatively
quickly after the book came out.

00:05:37.400 --> 00:05:40.770
I want to say, in two
or three weeks, maybe.

00:05:40.770 --> 00:05:44.990 position:56%
There was an interview I did with a
magazine, The American Conservative,

00:05:44.990 --> 00:05:46.860 position:56%
that went viral, as they say online.

00:05:46.860 --> 00:05:50.240
A lot of people were sharing it on
Twitter and Facebook and so forth,

00:05:50.240 --> 00:05:53.320
and I went to go check my
Amazon ranking, which, you know,

00:05:53.320 --> 00:05:55.210
those of you who have
written a book will know

00:05:55.210 --> 00:05:57.000
that your Amazon ranking
is a way to check

00:05:57.000 --> 00:05:59.290
in real time how your
book is actually selling.

00:05:59.290 --> 00:06:01.330
So there was a point in my
life where I was checking it

00:06:01.330 --> 00:06:06.210
like obsessively, probably
every 7 or 8 seconds.

00:06:06.210 --> 00:06:09.690
And I go to check my Amazon
ranking and it says, you know,

00:06:09.690 --> 00:06:12.510
like book is out of stock,
will ship in about a week.

00:06:12.510 --> 00:06:14.340
And I realized then that, oh, wow,

00:06:14.340 --> 00:06:16.270
we don't have enough
books that are out there.

00:06:16.270 --> 00:06:18.540
And so that's when they
really started to turn

00:06:18.540 --> 00:06:19.840
on the proverbial presses.

00:06:19.840 --> 00:06:21.140
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:So
how many, now,

00:06:21.140 --> 00:06:22.530
have been printed, would you say?

00:06:22.530 --> 00:06:25.310
&gt;&gt; J.D. Vance: So, I don't know
how many total are in print.

00:06:25.310 --> 00:06:29.870
I know that hard copies, we've
sold just under a million,

00:06:29.870 --> 00:06:32.710
and it's a little over a million
